The Bubble Sort algorithm works by repeatedly iterating through the array of Student objects and comparing adjacent elements. If the first element is greater than the second element, they swap positions. This process is repeated until no more swaps are needed, indicating that the array is sorted.

In the DisplayAll panel, the Bubble Sort algorithm is used to sort the array of Student objects in ascending order based on their names. The sorting is done by comparing the names using the String compareTo() method.

Here is an example implementation of the Bubble Sort algorithm in Java:

```
public void bubbleSort(Student[] students) {
    int n = students.length;
    boolean swapped;
    do {
        swapped = false;
        for (int I = 1; I < n; i++) {
            if (students[i-1].getName().compareTo(students[i].getName()) > 0) {
                // Swap the elements
                Student temp = students[i-1];
                students[i-1] = students[i];
                students[i] = temp;
                swapped = true;
            }
        }
        n--;
    } while (swapped);
}
```

This method takes an array of Student objects as input and sorts them using the Bubble Sort algorithm. The getName() method is assumed to return the name of the student as a String.

